 Section by Section Guide

  1. Abstract (half a page)

  Keep it short — 4–5 sentences covering:
  - What you built (IR system over Project Gutenberg)
  - What methods you used (inverted index, TF, VSM, BM25)
  - What you evaluated (6 queries, 3 models)
  - Key finding (which model performed best and why)

  ---
  2. Introduction (half to 1 page)

  Cover these points:
  - Problem: Finding relevant books in 70,000+ document collection
  - System architecture diagram — draw a simple flowchart:
  Books + Metadata → Preprocessing → Inverted Index → Query Parser → [Structured | VSM |
  BM25] → Ranked Results
  - Why IR is non-trivial (vocabulary mismatch, scale, ranking quality)
  - Brief overview of what each section covers

  ---
  3. Indexing (1–1.5 pages)

  This needs the most detail. Cover:

  Document Analysis & Preprocessing:
  - Unicode normalisation → lowercase → tokenisation → punctuation removal
  - Stop word removal for title/author fields (cite Manning §2.2.2)
  - Why stop words kept in body (queries like "to be or not to be" would return 0 results)
  - Porter stemmer (cite Manning §2.2.4)

  Index Construction:
  - Inverted index structure (cite Manning §1.2)
  - Three separate indexes: body_index, title_index, author_index
  - Why SQLite — persistence, fast lookup, no external library
  - Positional index for body — stores word positions as binary blobs (cite Manning §2.4.2)
  - Batch insert approach (BATCH_SIZE=500) for memory efficiency

  Data Structures:
  - Posting list: {term → [(doc_id, tf), ...]}
  - Metadata table: title, author, has_text flag
  - doc_lengths and avgdl tables for BM25 normalisation

  ---
  4. Ranking (1.5–2 pages)

  Describe all three models and why you chose those approaches:

  Query Parser:
  - Supports field:term, field:"phrase", plain terms
  - Unfielded terms broadcast to ALL fields (title + author + body)
  - Field weights: title=3.0, author=2.0, body=1.0 (cite Manning §6.1.1 weighted zone
  scoring)

  Structured Search (TF scoring):
  - Score = Σ field_weight × (tf / doc_len)
  - Simple, interpretable baseline
  - No IDF — doesn't penalise common terms

  VSM (TF-IDF Cosine Similarity):
  - TF: log(1 + tf) — cite Manning §6.4.1
  - IDF: log((N+1)/(df+1)) + 1 — smooth variant
  - Cosine normalisation by √doc_len
  - Why VSM: handles multi-term queries, ranks by semantic closeness to query vector

  BM25:
  - Full Okapi BM25 formula (cite Manning §11.4.3)
  - K1=1.5, B=0.75 — cite Manning for typical values
  - Why BM25: length normalisation, TF saturation, state-of-the-art bag-of-words model

